Book Seven seems to be annoyingly free from obvious nits or problems.
But I found a couple more &quot;semi-nits&quot;:

4. &quot;Just make sure your balance doesn't slip below a thousand Galleons.&quot;

Bellatrix Lestrange is a convicted multiple murderer. Her last act
before her capture was torturing Aurors Frank and Alice Longbottom into
insanity. She is complicite in the murders of goblins and is the
lieutenant of a Dark Lord who values all non-wizard lives at naught and
who has, in fact, personally broken into Gringott's and attempted to
steal an item of value. In Deathly Hallows Belletrix even imprisons a
goblin and mutilates him for no particular reason.

And yet, when Hermione arrives at Gringott's impersonating her, the head
goblin's only comment about her is:  'very old family..... old clients'
as he deferently hurries to help this old and valued customer down to
her vault.

Even for bankers this is a bit much. Well, okay. Maybe not.

On the upside, I suppose it means that Harry won't have any trouble
getting gold out of his vault, robbery and escape by dragon or no. The
goblin on duty will just respectfully show him to his gold. 'Good day,
sir, and thank you for banking with Gringott's'.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------- -------------------------------

5.  &quot;As Eihwaz going to St. Ives, I met a man with seven lives&quot;

The Tales of Beedle the Bard is written in runes and this, according to
Lovegood, makes it the original version. This would imply that the tales
are written in Anglo-Saxon, which Hermione has apparently translated
with the help of her Spellman's Syllabary.

Leaving aside the question of why a syllabary would be useful for
deciphering Anglo-Saxon runes, if the tales are in Anglo-Saxon, that
implies that Ignotus Peverell lived no later than, let's say, 1100 AD.

In that case, his gravestone is one of the oldest legible standing grave
markers in Britain. And it begs the question, why is there still room in
this churchyard for Harry's parents? Even if only wizards are buried
there, in nine centuries, that's still a lot of bodies piling up.

(Okay, this is a cheap nit. The runes are obviously there to suggest a
particular mythological idea, not to establish a date. Never the less,
it is a bit of a nit and is hearby officially picked.)
