Yeah, there is a saying that the best place to hide something is in
plain sight.

But it isn't true. :)

The best place to hide something is in a small cave facing the ocean and
accessible only at low tide--- and then only from a small pile of rocks
that would require superb mountaineering skill to reach. Inside the
cave, put the item behind a door that only someone of prodigious magical
skill could find. Then put additional protection in place to kill anyone
capable of finding it.

Now that's how you hide an item!

Dragon guarded vaults? Also good. Secret chamber that opens when
addressed in language known only to you? Superb. Dumping item on statue
in room available to anyone who needs to hide something? Not really
optimal. Giving item to Lucius Malfoy and asking him to keep an eye on
it? Priceless.

Hiding something in plain sight is only a good idea in books. That way
when the author reveals where the item was hidden, you kick yourself and
say: &quot;I should have thought of that&quot;.

But what you don't want is, when you read the reveal, to feel a impulse
to kick the author and say: &quot;I did think of that---- but rejected it as
too dumb.&quot;
